        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>battle card</strong> is a concise 1-2 page sales reference document that equips reps with competitive intelligence — key differentiators, objection handlers, landmine questions, and pricing traps — for positioning a product against a specific named competitor during live sales conversations. It exists to be scanned in under 60 seconds mid-call.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ideal length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1-2 pages</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Sales Enablement</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Win-rate impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">71% see lift (Crayon)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Refresh cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Quarterly minimum</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every rep will eventually hear "we're also evaluating [competitor]" on a discovery call. What happens in the next 30 seconds decides the deal. A good battle card turns that moment from ambush into ambush-in-reverse.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a battle card?</h2>
        <p>A battle card is an internal sales document — usually one to two pages — that a rep opens the second a prospect names a competitor. It compresses months of competitive research into scannable bullets, tables, and quotes so the rep can respond confidently instead of improvising.</p>
        <p>Battle cards are not brochures. They are not shared externally. They are working documents built for velocity — the rep has 15-45 seconds to find an answer while the prospect is talking, so density and hierarchy matter more than polish.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Industry benchmark</div>
          <p>Crayon's State of Competitive Intelligence report finds that <strong>71% of businesses using competitive intelligence tools</strong> — battle cards being the most common artifact — report a measurable win-rate impact. The teams that treat CI as a rep tool, not a leadership deck, capture the lift.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why battle cards matter</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Higher competitive win rates.</strong> Reps who cite specific, verifiable differentiators close competitive deals at 2-3x the rate of reps who default to feature-listing.</li>
          <li><strong>Consistent messaging across the team.</strong> Without battle cards, every rep positions the product slightly differently. Prospects notice, and it erodes trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Faster new-hire ramp.</strong> A new AE with good battle cards can defend against a named competitor within their first week, not their first quarter.</li>
          <li><strong>Objection preparation.</strong> The best cards list the exact three objections that competitor's reps use against you — and the response that neutralises each.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounds with win/loss data.</strong> Every deal that closes or dies feeds the next revision. Battle cards get sharper over time when the loop is closed.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How a battle card works</h2>
        <p>A useful battle card follows a repeatable structure. When a prospect says the competitor's name, the rep opens the card and finds the answer in one of five zones:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Snapshot</strong> — two to three neutral, factual sentences about the competitor. Never insult. Prospects trust reps who describe rivals accurately.</li>
          <li><strong>Key differentiators</strong> — three to five concrete differences with proof points. Not "we're better at X" but "we do X in Y minutes; their public docs show Z minutes".</li>
          <li><strong>Objection handlers</strong> — the exact language for the three most common objections a rep hears when this competitor is in play.</li>
          <li><strong>Landmines / traps</strong> — questions the rep can plant that surface the competitor's weaknesses without seeming aggressive ("How does their platform handle X on mobile?").</li>
          <li><strong>Pricing intelligence</strong> — the competitor's list price, discount patterns, and typical contract terms so the rep is not surprised by pricing pressure.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Types of battle cards</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Focus</th><th>Best use</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Competitor battle card</strong></td><td>One named rival</td><td>The default — most common format</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Persona battle card</strong></td><td>One buyer type (e.g. CFO)</td><td>Complex-buying committees, ABM motions</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Industry battle card</strong></td><td>One vertical's language, KPIs, workflows</td><td>Multi-vertical products, field sales teams</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Objection battle card</strong></td><td>One recurring objection ("too expensive")</td><td>Later-stage negotiation coaching</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Landmine card</strong></td><td>Discovery questions that surface pain</td><td>SDR / BDR outbound teams</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real battle card examples</h2>

        <h3>1. SaaS competitive card — Slack vs Microsoft Teams (rep-side)</h3>
        <p>Zone 1 (snapshot): three sentences on Teams' bundling with Microsoft 365. Zone 2 (differentiators): search speed, integration count, threading UX with numeric proof. Zone 3 (objection): "But Teams is free with our license" — response: "It is bundled, not free — here is the productivity cost we saw at [customer]." Zone 4 (landmine): "How does your team handle deep-linked threads across channels?"</p>

        <h3>2. B2B service card — agency vs in-house hire</h3>
        <p>A marketing agency's card for the "we might just hire someone" objection: cost comparison of one FTE salary + benefits vs 12-month retainer, ramp-time delta, breadth-of-skill comparison, and the exit-risk framing ("what happens when they quit?").</p>

        <h3>3. Ecommerce card — DTC brand vs Amazon listing</h3>
        <p>A Shopify brand's card for reps handling wholesale objections: margin comparison, brand-control examples, one paragraph of Amazon-fatigue signals, and three questions to ask a buyer that surface Amazon-dependency risk.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Battle card vs sales one-pager — which one you need</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a battle card when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The prospect has named a specific competitor</li>
              <li>The rep needs a fast, internal reference</li>
              <li>You have real win/loss data to draw from</li>
              <li>Competitive deals are a large share of pipeline</li>
              <li>You want message consistency across a growing team</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a one-pager when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You need something to leave behind after a meeting</li>
              <li>The audience is the prospect, not the rep</li>
              <li>It is early in the funnel with no rival yet</li>
              <li>You need something a champion can circulate internally</li>
              <li>Product overview matters more than competitive positioning</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for building a battle card</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Interview 5 reps before writing anything.</strong> Ask which competitors they lose to, which objections come up, and which of their current answers actually work.</li>
          <li><strong>Cap it at two pages.</strong> If it does not fit on two pages, split it. Reps do not scroll on live calls.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead with the top three differentiators, not ten.</strong> A card with ten differentiators is a card with zero — the rep cannot pick fast enough.</li>
          <li><strong>Include exact language, not concepts.</strong> Write the sentence you want the rep to say aloud. Concept-level guidance ("emphasise reliability") gets improvised badly.</li>
          <li><strong>Cite the source of every claim.</strong> Reps will not repeat a statistic they cannot verify. Link to the review, doc, or win-report.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh quarterly, patch immediately.</strong> Quarterly rebuilds catch drift. Same-day patches after a competitor's launch prevent field embarrassment.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — battle cards written by marketing alone</div>
          <p>Cards written without rep input read like blog posts. Reps ignore them. The cards that survive are co-authored: product marketing brings competitive research, sales brings the real objections, revenue ops closes the loop with win/loss data.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common battle card mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Bashing the competitor.</strong> Prospects reward the seller who describes rivals fairly. Aggressive cards lose trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Too many differentiators.</strong> Ten is worse than three. Reps cannot pick under time pressure.</li>
          <li><strong>Feature parity walls.</strong> Long feature-comparison tables read like defensive product docs. Focus on the two or three things that decide the deal.</li>
          <li><strong>Never updated.</strong> A card that mentions your competitor's Q2 2024 pricing in 2026 destroys rep credibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Buried in Google Drive.</strong> If the card is not in the CRM or sales-enablement platform where reps live, it will not get opened.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>theStacc builds the underlying content layer — customer stories, comparison pages, and category research — that feeds a strong battle card. When your <a href="/blog/">blog</a>, <a href="/glossary/competitive-analysis/">competitive analysis</a>, and case studies actually cite verifiable numbers, product marketing has proof points to drop into every card. Weak content stacks produce weak battle cards.</p>

